@rahul003

When running an OBJ through the OBJ exporter, the mesh names are all duplicated. If you take the output of an exported OBJ and then run it through AssImp OBJExporter again it will further duplicate the mesh names. They continue to double every time it is run through the exporter.

The line causing the issue is here: https://github.com/assimp/assimp/blob/master/code/ObjExporter.cpp#L351

I fixed this issue for us by changing the line to this: mesh.name = std::string(name.data,name.length);

Moved from https://github.com/aws/aws-cli/issues/2903

```bash
aws --version
# Output
aws-cli/1.11.171 Python/3.6.3 Darwin/16.7.0 botocore/1.7.29
```

Overview: The `ecr get-lifecycle-policy` returns a mix of quote-escaped JSON and regular JSON. This results in a JSON Object being of the STRING type.

Current Behaviour:
```bash
aws ecr get-lifecycle-policy --repository-name some-repo
#Output
{
    "registryId": "**********15",
    "repositoryName": "some-repo",
    "lifecyclePolicyText": "{\"rules\":[{\"rulePriority\":10,\"description\":\"remove old untagged images\",\"selection\":{\"tagStatus\":\"untagged\",\"countType\":\"sinceImagePushed\",\"countUnit\":\"days\",\"countNumber\":30},\"action\":{\"type\":\"expire\"}},{\"rulePriority\":20,\"description\":\"Old tags\",\"selection\":{\"tagStatus\":\"tagged\",\"tagPrefixList\":[\"201\"],\"countType\":\"sinceImagePushed\",\"countUnit\":\"days\",\"countNumber\":30},\"action\":{\"type\":\"expire\"}}]}",
    "lastEvaluatedAt": 1508261466.0
}
```

Expected Behaviour:
```bash
aws ecr get-lifecycle-policy --repository-name some-repo
#Output
{
    "registryId": "**********15",
    "repositoryName": "some-repo",
    "lifecyclePolicyText": {
        "rules ": [{
            "rulePriority ": 10,
            "description ": "remove old untagged images ",
            "selection ": {
                "tagStatus ": "untagged ",
                "countType ": "sinceImagePushed ",
                "countUnit ": "days ",
                "countNumber ": 30
            },
            "action ": {
                "type ": "expire "
            }
        }, {
            "rulePriority ": 20,
            "description ": "Old tags ",
            "selection ": {
                "tagStatus ": "tagged ",
                "tagPrefixList ": ["201 "],
                "countType ": "sinceImagePushed ",
                "countUnit ": "days ",
                "countNumber ": 30
            },
            "action ": {
                "type ": "expire "
            }
        }]
    },
    "lastEvaluatedAt": 1508261466.0
}
```

In this minimal example:
```
from datapackage import Package

DESCRIPTOR = {
  'resources': [
    {
      'name': 'teams',
      'data': [
        ['id'],
        [1.0],
        [2.0]
      ],
      'schema': {
        'fields': [
          {'name': 'id', 'type': 'integer'}
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}

# Check
package = Package(DESCRIPTOR)
teams = package.get_resource('teams')
teams.read()

```
the `teams.read()` raises a `CastError` triggered by the `1.0` float. If it is represented a `1` or as `'1'` there are no `CastError`s.
Perhaps enable automatic casting of `float` to `int` or document the behavior.

First of all, I would like to say that I love how .NET Core projects can automatically manage package dependencies. Brilliant.

Hence I began developing projects using ASP.NET MVC Core, albeit still using the full .NET 4.5 instead of .NET Core due to various reasons. So my class libraries `project.json` often ended up like this:

```json
{
  "version": "1.0.0-*",

  "dependencies": {
  },

  "frameworks": {
    "net45": {
    }
  }
}
```

Which is great and works beautifully in MVC Core land. However, as soon as someone need `Add Reference` to my class libraries without being packaged into NuGet packages (actually I haven't tried packaging those classes into NuGet packages, but I don't see why they wouldn't work), this happens:

```
---------------------------
Microsoft Visual Studio
---------------------------
A reference to 'My.Class.Library' could not be added. An assembly must have a 'dll' or 'exe' extension in order to be referenced.
---------------------------
OK   
---------------------------
```

I realized that this scenario is the opposite of the ".NET Core project needs to reference the .NET 4.5 DLLs", but is it possible to have this feature for convenience?

